      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "496adf3e59c9c407",
        "text": "Moreover, communication, if one does not already read action into it, is a symmetrical relation of several selections. This, too, is obscured by the metaphor of transmission. Communication is symmetrical insofar as each selection can lead the others and the leading relations can be continuously reversed. At times the bottleneck and focus is in what can be understood; at other times new information takes precedence, and soon after the need to communicate as such strikes through. Thus, there is no once-and-for-all fixed direction of selection reinforcement. The conditions are reversible and insofar highly adaptable. Only through the incorporation of an understanding of action into the communicative event does communication become asymmetrical, only through this does it acquire a direction from the communicator to the recipient of the communication, which can only be reversed by the recipient of the communication in turn beginning to communicate something, i.e. to act."
      },
      "date": 1681307543962
    },
